# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: auxiliary-power-unit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/abc-motors] The ABC radial aero engines of the World War I period were extremely advanced for their time, and were initially thought to be very promising indeed.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/abc-motors] Unfortunately they were all more or less plagued by problems – and although a number of types for the Royal Air Force were designed around ABC engines (especially the ill-fated *Dragonfly*) none saw squadron service with the RAF.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/abc-motors] ABC also made a large number of engines for electrical generators and other purposes – mostly with a flat twin cylinder layout and unusual exhaust-over-inlet valve configuration.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] An **adaptive compliant wing** is a wing which is flexible enough for aspects of its shape to be changed in flight.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible wings have a number of benefits.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Conventional flight control mechanisms operate using hinges, resulting in disruptions to the airflow, vortices, and in some cases, separation of the airflow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] These effects contribute to the drag of the aircraft, resulting in less efficiency and higher fuel costs.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible aerofoils can manipulate aerodynamic forces with less disruptions to the flow, resulting in less aerodynamic drag and improved fuel economy.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changing the shape of an aerodynamic surface has a direct effect on its aerodynamic properties.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] According to the flow condition and to the initial shape of the part, each shape variation (curvature, incidence, twist...) can have a different impact on the resulting forces and moments.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] This characteristic is actively pursued in adaptive wings which – by nature of their distributed compliance – can attain shape changes in a continuous, smooth, gap-free manner.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] By altering these geometrical parameters, the forces and moments can be modified, permitting to tailor them to the specific flight condition (e.g. for drag reduction) or to perform maneuvers (e.g. roll).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Shape adaptation can be classified according to the motion it enables.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changes of the airfoil shapes include altering its twist, and changing its camber and thickness distribution.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] An adaptive compliant wing designed by FlexSys Inc. features a variable-camber trailing edge which can be deflected up to ±10°, thus acting like a flap-equipped wing, but without the individual segments and gaps typical in a flap system.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing itself can be twisted up to 1° per foot of span.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing's shape can be changed at a rate of 30° per second, which is ideal for gust load alleviation.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The development of the adaptive compliant wing is being sponsored by the U.S.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Initially, the wing was tested in a wind tunnel, and then a 50-inch (1.3 m) section of wing was flight tested on board the Scaled Composites White Knight research aircraft in a seven-flight, 20-hour program operated from the Mojave Spaceport.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Adaptive compliant wings are also investigated at ETH Zurich in the frame of the Smart airfoil project.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The EU-funded Flexop program aims to develop to enable higher wing aspect ratio for less induced drag with lighter, more flexible airliner wings, along developing active flutter suppression for flexible wings.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Partners include Hungary's MTA SZTAKI, Airbus, Austria's FACC, Inasco of Greece, Delft University of Technology, German aerospace center DLR, TUM, the UK's University of Bristol and RWTH Aachen University in Germany.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] On 19 November 2019, a 7 m (23 ft) span jet-powered UAV demonstrator with an aeroelastically tailored wing for passive load alleviation was flown in Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany, previously flown with a carbon-fiber, rigid wing to establish baseline performance.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] It has a conventional tube-and-wing configuration, unlike the blended wing body of the Lockheed Martin X-56.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] It follows the Grumman X-29 demonstrator in 1984, with more refined fiber orientations.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The flexible wing is 4% lighter than the rigid one.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The 54-month, €6.67 million ($7.4 million) project ends in November 2019, followed by the €3.85 million FLiPASED program from September 2019 until December 2022, using all the movable surfaces.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The glass fiber flutter wing should to be flown in 2020, with unstable aeroelastic modes under 55 m/s (107 kn) that must be actively suppressed.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] With optimized aeroelastic tailoring and active flutter suppression, an aspect ratio of 12.4 could reduce fuel-burn by 5%, and 7% are targeted.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/adaptive-compliant-wing] FLiPASED is also led by MTA SZTAKI and include partners TUM, DLR and French aerospace research agency ONERA.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerodynamics] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aerosila] Since 1956 the enterprise started creation of auxiliary gas-turbine engines for APU.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The **aft pressure bulkhead** or **rear pressure bulkhead** is the rear component of the pressure seal in all aircraft that cruise in a tropopause zone in the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] It helps maintain pressure when stratocruising and protects the aircraft from bursting due to the higher internal pressure.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Aft pressure bulkheads can either be curved, which reduces the amount of metal needed at the cost of reducing the usable space in the airliner, or flat, which gives more internal space but also more weight.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Patents have been filed that propose deliberately creating cavities within the rear bulkhead with the purpose of providing more usable cabin space.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] On several airliners, production of the rear pressure bulkhead has been outsourced to third party manufacturers.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] While typically being a time-consuming and somewhat uncommon process, an aircraft's aft pressure bulkhead can be wholly replaced.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During the twenty-first century, various parties became increasingly interested in developing aft pressure bulkheads composed from composite materials, seeking benefits such as lower manufacturing costs, easier sealing, elimination of corrosion risk, along with weight and part count reductions.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During the early 2000s, Airbus Group developed the largest manufactured resin film infusion structure then in production to function as the aft pressure bulkhead for their double-decker A380 airliner.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Multiple instances of damage to the aft pressure bulkhead have occurred; while a few cases have led to serious failures leading to aircraft losses, others have proven to be survivable.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Aviation certifying authorities have often mandated inspections of an aircraft's aft pressure bulkhead in the interest of safety.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Various techniques have been devised to determine the integrity of the rear pressure bulkhead; these have been used not only to inspect in-service examples but also in the design process, helping to design efficient bulkheads that possess sufficient strength to ensure a safe operational life.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] In 1971, British European Airways Flight 706 crashed in Belgium, killing all 63 on board; the cause was determined to be corrosion of the rear pressure bulkhead by fluid contamination, perhaps from the lavatory.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The corrosion was not detectable by the inspection techniques at the time.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] In 1985, Japan Air Lines Flight 123 crashed after a catastrophic failure of the aft pressure bulkhead.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] The failure occurred due to faulty repair of the bulkhead after a tailstrike seven years earlier, when a single repair patch plate was incorrectly cut in two "to make it fit".
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Failure of the bulkhead damaged hydraulic pipes passing through.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] Boeing later calculated that the incorrect installation would be expected to fail after approximately 10,000 pressurizations; the repaired aircraft accomplished 12,318 successful flights before the crash.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/aft-pressure-bulkhead] During 2013, National Airlines Flight 102 crashed after loose freight on the main deck is believed to have penetrated the aft pressure bulkhead and caused damage to control systems in the vicinity of the bulkhead.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] An **auxiliary power unit**(**APU**) is a device on a vehicle that provides energy for functions other than propulsion.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] They are commonly found on large aircraft, naval ships and some large land vehicles.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Aircraft APUs generally produce 115 V AC at 400 Hz (rather than the 50 or 60 Hz common in mains supplies), to run the electrical systems of the aircraft; others can produce 28 V DC.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] APUs can provide power through single- or three-phase systems.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] A **jet fuel starter** (**JFS**) is a device similar to an APU but directly linked to a main engine and started by an onboard compressed air bottle.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] During World War I, the British Coastal class blimps, one of several types of airship operated by the Royal Navy, carried a 1.75 horsepower (1.30 kW) ABC auxiliary engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] These powered a generator for the craft's radio transmitter and, in an emergency, could power an auxiliary air blower.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] One of the first military fixed-wing aircraft to use an APU was the British, World War 1, Supermarine Nighthawk, an anti-Zeppelin night fighter.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] During World War II, a number of large American military aircraft were fitted with APUs.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] These were typically known as *putt–putts*, even in official training documents.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The putt-putt on the B-29 Superfortress bomber was fitted in the unpressurised section at the rear of the aircraft.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Various models of four-stroke flat-twin or V-twin engines were used.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The 7-horsepower (5.2 kW) engine drove a *P2*, DC generator, rated 28.5 volts and 200 amps (several of the same *P2* generators, driven by the main engines, were the B-29's DC power source in flight).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The putt-putt provided power for starting the main engines and was used after take-off to a height of 10,000 feet (3,000 m).
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The putt-putt was restarted when the B-29 was descending to land.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Some models of the B-24 Liberator had a putt–putt fitted at the front of the aircraft, inside the nose-wheel compartment.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Some models of the Douglas C-47 Skytrain transport aircraft carried a putt-putt under the cockpit floor.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The first German jet engines built during the Second World War used a mechanical APU starting system designed by the German engineer Norbert Riedel.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] It consisted of a 10 horsepower (7.5 kW) two-stroke flat engine, which for the Junkers Jumo 004 design was hidden in the engine nose cone, essentially functioning as a pioneering example of an auxiliary power unit for starting a jet engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] A hole in the extreme nose of the cone contained a manual pull-handle which started the piston engine, which in turn rotated the compressor.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Two spark plug access ports existed in the Jumo 004's nose cone to service the Riedel unit's cylinders in situ, for maintenance purposes.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Two small "premix" tanks for the Riedel's petrol/oil fuel were fitted in the annular intake.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The engine was considered an extreme short stroke (bore / stroke: 70 mm / 35 mm = 2:1) design so it could fit within the in the nose cone of jet engines like the Jumo 004.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] For reduction it had an integrated planetary gear.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The Boeing 727 in 1963 was the first jetliner to feature a gas turbine APU, allowing it to operate at smaller airports, independent from ground facilities.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The APU can be identified on many modern airliners by an exhaust pipe at the aircraft's tail.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The power section is the gas-generator portion of the engine and produces all the shaft power for the APU.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] In this section of the engine, air and fuel are mixed, compressed and ignited to create hot and expanding gases.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] This gas is highly energetic and is used to spin the turbine, which in turn powers other sections of the engine, such as auxiliary gearboxes, pumps, electrical generators, and in the case of a turbo fan engine, the main fan.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The load compressor is generally a shaft-mounted compressor that provides pneumatic power for the aircraft, though some APUs extract bleed air from the power section compressor.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] There are two actuated devices to help control the flow of air: the inlet guide vanes that regulate airflow to the load compressor and the surge control valve that maintains stable or surge-free operation of the turbo machine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The gearbox transfers power from the main shaft of the engine to an oil-cooled generator for electrical power.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Within the gearbox, power is also transferred to engine accessories such as the fuel control unit, the lubrication module, and cooling fan.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] There is also a starter motor connected through the gear train to perform the starting function of the APU.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Some APU designs use a combination starter/generator for APU starting and electrical power generation to reduce complexity.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] On the Boeing 787, an aircraft which has greater reliance on its electrical systems, the APU delivers only electricity to the aircraft.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The absence of a pneumatic system simplifies the design, but high demand for electricity requires heavier generators.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Onboard solid oxide fuel cell (SOFC) APUs are being researched.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The market of Auxiliary power units is dominated by Honeywell, followed by Pratt & Whitney (a subsidiary of RTX Corporation), Motorsich and other manufacturers such as PBS Velká Bíteš, Safran Power Units, Aerosila and Klimov.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] On June 4, 2018, Boeing and Safran announced their 50–50 partnership to design, build and service APUs after regulatory and antitrust clearance in the second half of 2018.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Boeing produced several hundred T50/T60 small turboshafts and their derivatives in the early 1960s.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Safran produces helicopters and business jets APUs but stopped the large APUs since Labinal exited the APIC joint venture with Sundstrand in 1996.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] A journalist from the online news website *FlightGlobal*, Stephen Trimble, has stated that Boeing and Safran's advances in the market for APUs pose a threat for the duopoly between Honeywell and Pratt & Whitney.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Honeywell has a 65% share of the mainliner APU market and is the sole supplier for the Airbus A350, the Boeing 777 and all single-aisles: the Boeing 737 MAX, Airbus A220 (formerly Bombardier CSeries), Comac C919, Irkut MC-21 and Airbus A320neo since Airbus eliminated the P&WC APS3200 option.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] P&WC claims the remaining 35% with the Airbus A380, Boeing 787 and Boeing 747-8.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] It should take at least a decade for the Boeing/Safran JV to reach $100 million in service revenue.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The 2017 market for production was worth $800 million (88% civil and 12% military), while the MRO market was worth $2.4 billion, spread equally between civil and military.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The Space Shuttle APUs provided hydraulic pressure.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The Space Shuttle had three redundant APUs, powered by hydrazine fuel.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] They were only powered up for ascent, re-entry, and landing.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] During ascent, the APUs provided hydraulic power for gimballing of the Shuttle's three engines and control of their large valves, and for movement of the control surfaces.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] During landing, they moved the control surfaces, lowered the wheels, and powered the brakes and nose-wheel steering.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Landing could be accomplished with only one APU working.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] In the early years of the Shuttle there were problems with APU reliability, with malfunctions on three of the first nine Shuttle missions.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] APUs are fitted to some tanks to provide electrical power without the high fuel consumption and large infrared signature of the main engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] As early as World War II, the American M4 Sherman had a small, piston-engine powered APU for charging the tank's batteries, a feature the Soviet-produced T-34 tank did not have.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The United States Army Tank Automotive Research, Development and Engineering Center (TARDEC) developed a 100 kg auxiliary power unit (APU) for the M1 Abrams tank to replace a 230 kg battery.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The new APU will also be more fuel-efficient than the tank's main engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] A refrigerated or frozen food semi trailer or train car may be equipped with an independent APU and fuel tank to maintain low temperatures for the cargo while in transit, without the need for an external transport-supplied power source.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] On some older diesel engined-equipment, a small gasoline engine (often called a "pony engine") was used instead of an electric motor to start the main engine.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] The exhaust path of the pony engine was typically arranged so as to warm the intake manifold of the diesel, to ease starting in colder weather.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] These were primarily used on large pieces of construction equipment.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] In recent years, truck and fuel cell manufacturers have teamed up to create, test and demonstrate a fuel cell APU that eliminates nearly all emissions and uses diesel fuel more efficiently.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] In 2008, a DOE sponsored partnership between Delphi Electronics and Peterbilt demonstrated that a fuel cell could provide power to the electronics and air conditioning of a Peterbilt Model 386 under simulated "idling" conditions for ten hours.
[src:auxiliary-power-unit/auxiliary-power-unit] Delphi has said the 5 kW system for Class 8 trucks will be released in 2012, at an $8000–9000 price tag that would be competitive with other "midrange" two-cylinder diesel APUs, should they be able to meet those deadlines and cost estimates.
